For every frame (per person), they have a 'bounding box' recording their coordinates in the x & y plane, along with 17 key points.
Bounding box = [x1, x2, y1, y2]
  - A box that encircles their entire body. 
Keypoint index map:
0: nose          1: left_eye       2: right_eye
3: left_ear      4: right_ear      5: left_shoulder
6: right_shoulder  7: left_elbow   8: right_elbow
9: left_wrist    10: right_wrist  11: left_hip
12: right_hip    13: left_knee    14: right_knee
15: left_ankle   16: right_ankle

The logic will be stored in classifiers.py. 
Data flow:
Webcam (React)
  → useCamera.js extracts frame every 2s
  → useDetection.js POSTs base64 frame to FastAPI /analyze
  → FastAPI runs YOLOv8 → classifiers.py → returns events JSON
  → React receives result → if alert, POSTs to Node server
  → Node Socket.io broadcasts to ALL connected dashboards
  → AlertPanel.jsx renders the alert in real time

Event 1: Lying Down / Fallen
  When standing:  bounding box height >> width  (tall)
  When lying:     bounding box width >> height  (wide)
  
  Rule: if (box_width / box_height) > 1.4  →  LYING_DOWN
  
  Stronger check: are shoulder_y, hip_y, and ankle_y all roughly equal?
  If yes → person is horizontal → FALLEN

Event 2: Not Moving / Stationary
  YOLOv8-Pose has built-in tracking (model.track()) which assigns a stable ID to each person across frames. Use this.
  For each person_id, keep a list of their (timestamp, x, y) center positions.
  
  Every frame, check:
    total distance moved in last 15 seconds < 20 pixels?
    → STATIONARY alert
  
  This lives in tracker.py — a dict of deques, keyed by track_id.

Event 3: Erratic Movement
  Opposite of stationary — person is moving a LOT but inconsistently.
  
  Calculate frame-to-frame movement deltas from the position history.
    mean_delta = average pixels moved per frame
    std_delta  = how variable those movements are
  
  If mean_delta > 10 AND (std_delta / mean_delta) > 0.8  →  ERRATIC
  
  High variance relative to mean = chaotic, unpredictable movement.

Event 5: Crouching / Hunched Over
  Compare nose_y to hip_y.
  
  When standing:  nose_y is much higher (lower number) than hip_y
  When crouched:  nose_y approaches hip_y
  
  Rule: if (hip_y - nose_y) < 0.3 * bounding_box_height  →  CROUCHING
  
  Useful for detecting someone collapsed against a wall or doubled over.
